        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <salute>My dear Miss I.</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I have received from my niece your letter to her (in which you say you w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> like to undertake the situation of sec. to Mr D. your testimonials are most satisfactory &amp; I will carefully return them to you—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>It is so very doubtful Mr Darwin being able to dictate to his own satisfaction or employ a sec. that I think the best plan would be if you wd come &amp; spend a few days with us that you may judge you may see whether the whole thing &amp; accommodations in the village w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> suit you; &amp; if so Mr D. w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> be glad to make the experiment for about a month.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>If you will appoint the 1<hi rend="superscript">st</hi> day next week that will suit you we will meet you at W. Croydon Station at any hour of the afternoon that you will fix— M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Darwin is so m. of an invalid that I will not ask you to spend the evening w. us but I hope you will</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is established by the reference in <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1218.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emma Darwin’s</ref> diary (DAR 242) to Isitt’s visit from 18 to 20 September 1871.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Emma may refer to Frances Julia (Snow) Wedgwood, who had a number of literary connections, probably including the Tennysons; <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_5307.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Virginia Lavinia Isitt</ref> had formerly worked for <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_6004.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Emily Jesse</ref>, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4696.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Alfred Tennyson’s</ref> sister (Wedgwood and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8245.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Wedgwood 1980</ref>; <ref target="" resp="#automat">letter from Emma Darwin to Henrietta Emma Darwin, [17 September 1871]</ref> (DAR 219.9: 95)).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Isitt only stayed for two days (see n. 1, above). She probably stayed at Down House with the Darwin family; Emma wrote to her daughter Henrietta on 17 September 1871 that they were having trouble finding accommodation for Isitt in the village; ‘[the villagers] do not like to undertake a young lady they require so m. attendance’ (DAR 219.9: 95).</note>
        </div>        
            
